Public Prosecutor v Loh Kaine Tong Nicholas
[2023] SGDC 46

Case Number:District Arrest Case No 907784-2022, Magistrate's Appeal No 9037-2023-01
Decision Date:09 March 2023
Tribunal/Court:District Court
Coram: Salina Bte Ishak
Counsel Name(s): Yap Poh Huat (Criminal Investigation Department) for the Prosecution; Desmond Tan Yen Hau (Lee & Lee) for the accused.
Parties: Public Prosecutor — Loh Kaine Tong Nicholas

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Statutory Offences – Road Traffic Act – Driving without due care and attention causing grievous hurt

[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9037/2023/01.]

9 March 2023

District Judge Salina Bte Ishak:

Background

1       The accused, Mr Loh Kaine Tong Nicholas, a 32-year-old male Singapore citizen faced the following charges:

DAC 907784-2022

Charge (Amended)

are charged that on 7 March 2020 at or about 4.25 pm, along Lornie Road towards the direction of Braddell Road at opposite lamp post 27, Singapore, did drive a motor car, SKE4289B on a road without due care and attention, to wit, by failing to have proper control of your vehicle while going over a puddle of water, resulted the vehicle to lose control, mounted up the centre kerb, uprooted 1 portion of guard railing, and collided head-on with motor car SLN8546Z who was travelling along Lornie Road towards Adam Road with grievous hurt caused to the driver namely Wai Chee Meng, male 53 years old and 1 passenger of motor car SLN8546Z namely S Dharunya Ivana, female 9 years old and you have thereby committed an offence under Section 65(1)(a) punishable under Section 65(3)(a) read with Section 65(6) (d) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (“RTA”).

DAC 907786-2022

Charge (Amended)

are charged that on 7 March 2020 at or about 4.25 pm, along Lornie Road towards the direction of Braddell Road at opposite lamp post 27, Singapore, did drive a motor car, SKE4289B on a road without due care and attention, to wit, by failing to have proper control of your vehicle while going over a puddle of water, resulted the vehicle to lose control, mounted up the centre kerb, uprooted 1 portion of guard railing, and collided head-on with motor car SLN8546Z who was travelling along Lornie Road towards Adam Road with hurt caused to your front passenger namely Ng Xue Min, female 32 years old and passenger of SLN8546Z namely Jayaraj Chandra, female 36 years old and you have thereby committed an offence under Section 65(1)(a) punishable under Section 65(4)(a) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (“RTA”).

2       On 13 February 2023, the accused pleaded guilty to the charge in DAC 907784-2022 and admitted to the Statement of Facts without any qualification. The remaining charge in DAC 907786-2022 was taken into consideration for the purpose of sentence.

3       After carefully considering the Prosecution’s address on sentence as well as the Defence’s plea in mitigation, I sentenced the accused to five weeks’ imprisonment and disqualified him from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of five years with effect from the date of release. As the accused sought a deferment of his sentence for him to settle his personal matters, I had initially ordered his sentence to commence on 13 March 2023.

4       The accused being dissatisfied with my decision had filed his Notice of Appeal against my sentence on 24 February 2023. He is on bail pending the hearing of his appeal.

5       Having set out the background for the present case, I now provide the reasons for my decision.

Salient Facts

6       The accused was the driver of motor car SKE4289B (Toyota Corolla Altis) at the time of accident.

Victims

7       The victims were:

(a)     Wai Chee Meng, male Chinese, Singaporean aged 53 years old. (“first victim”). He was the driver of motor car SLN8546Z at the time of accident.

(b)     S Dharunya Ivana, female Indian, Singaporean aged 9 years old. (“second victim”). She was the rear left passenger of motor car SLN8546Z at the time of accident.

(c)     Jayaraj Chandra, Female Indian, India National aged 36 years old. (“third victim”). She was the rear right passenger of motor car SLN8546Z at the time of accident and

(d)     Ng Xue Min, Female Chinese, Singaporean aged 32 years old. (“fourth victim”). She was the front passenger of motor car SKE4289B at the time of accident.

8       On 7 March 2020 at about 4.25pm, the accused was driving his motor car SKE4289B along Lornie Road towards the direction of Braddell Road at opposite lamp post 27, Singapore, without due care and attention, to wit, by failing to have proper control of his vehicle while going over a puddle of water, resulted the vehicle to lose control, mounted up the centre kerb, uprooted one portion of guard railing, and collided head-on with motor car SLN8546Z which was travelling along Lornie Road towards Adam Road. Due to the collision, grievous hurt was caused to first and second victims.

9       As a result of the accident, the first victim was conveyed to Tan Tock Seng Hospital (TTSH) by ambulance. X-rays of the left ankle and foot performed on 7 March 2020 showed a comminuted fracture of the left calcaneum, with intraarticular involvement, as well as significant surrounding soft tissue swelling. He was hospitalised from 7 March 2020 to 12 March 2020 before being discharged with 50 days of medical leave. He was readmitted on 27 March 2020 and underwent left calcaneus corrective osteotomy and surgical fixation on the same day. He was discharged on 2 April 2020 with medical leave until 23 July 2020. His total hospitalisation leave was 139 days.

10     The second victim was conveyed to KK Women’s and Children’s Hospital by ambulance. She had sustained a right tibia fracture and underwent a closed reduction and elastic nailing of the right tibia on 8 March 2020. She was hospitalised from 7 March 2020 to 13 March 2020 and given 20 days of hospitalization leave till 27 March 2020. Her titanium elastic nail was removed on 24 September 2020.

11     The third victim was conveyed to TTSH by ambulance. She had sustained facial lacerations and was referred to plastics surgery team. She underwent debridement and suturing of the facial lacerations on 7 March 2020. The third victim also sustained lung contusion and internal oblique muscle haematoma and right lower lateral incisor fracture and was hospitalised from 7 March 2020 to 9 March 2020 before being discharged with 14 days of medical leave.

12     The fourth victim was conveyed to TTSH by ambulance. She had sustained left neck abrasion, right knee and hip abrasion and was hospitalised from 7 March 2020 to 8 March 2020 before being discharged with 16 days of medical leave.

Property damage

13     The damage to the first victim’s motor car were:

(a)     Right side mirror twisted.

(b)     Front windscreen cracked.

(c)     Front portion cracked, crumpled, scratched, dented and twisted.

14     The damage to the accused’s motor car were:

(a)     Front portion cracked, crumpled, scratched, dented and twisted.

(b)     Front and rear windscreen cracked.

(c)     Rear portion cracked, crumpled, scratched, dented, ripped off and twisted.

15     In addition, one portion of guard railing was uprooted.

Speed of accused’s vehicle

16     Forensic Scientist, Yeo Soon Yong of the Forensic Chemistry and Physics Laboratory from the Health Science Authority (“HSA”) conducted a sequence of events, speed analysis of the accused’s motor car. He found that the accused was travelling at an estimated average speed of 87km/h to 98 km/h in the 17 seconds prior to him losing control of his motorcar. In the last 3 seconds, the estimated average travelling speed was 88km/h to 102 km/h. It was established that the road speed limit for the incident location is 70km/h.

Footage

17     The footage from the accused’s motor car revealed that while he was driving his motor car SKE4289B along Lornie Road towards the direction of Braddell Road at opposite lamp post 27, he lost control of his vehicle while going over a puddle of water, mounted up the centre kerb, uprooted one portion of guard railing, and collided head-on with motor car SLN8546Z who was travelling opposite direction of the expressway.

18     At the time of the accident, it was raining, the road surface was wet, the traffic volume was moderate and the visibility was good.

Sentencing

Prescribed Penalty

19     The prescribed penalty for an offence of driving without due care and attention under s 65(1)(a) and punishable ss 65(3)(a) read with 65(6)(d) of the Road Traffic Act (“RTA”) is fine not exceeding $5,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 2 years or to both. In addition, the offender is liable to a mandatory disqualification order for all classes of vehicles for at least five years.

Antecedents

20     The accused is untraced.

Prosecution’s Submissions on Sentence

Culpability

21     The Prosecution sought the imposition of a fine of $4,000 to $5,000 and a disqualification for 5 years. It was submitted that the accused’s culpability should be pegged at higher end of low. Based on the HSA speed analysis, he was travelling at a speed higher than the speed limit of the road. His estimated speed was 88 to 102 km/h which exceeded the speed limit of 70 km/h and minimally it was 18 km/h in excess.

Harm

22     In respect of harm, it was highlighted that there were four victims. In respect of the proceeded charge, the first victim suffered several fractures and underwent surgical fixation and was hospitalised for total of 12 days with 139 days of medical leave. The second victim, a 9-year-old child, sustained a right tibia fracture and underwent an elastic nailing of the rib tibia. She was hospitalised for 7 days and was given 20 days of medical leave. As such the level of harm should be pegged at moderate.

23     Applying the sentencing framework set by the High Court in Sue Chang (Xu Zheng) v Public Prosecutor [2022] SGHC 176 (“Sue Chang”), the present case fell within the sentencing range of a fine or up to four months imprisonment. As such, it was submitted that a fine of between $4,000 to $5,000 and of disqualification of 5 years was just fair and appropriate.

Mitigation

24     It was submitted that the accused is a safe driver. That was his first major accident and prior to this incident he had never been convicted of any serious road traffic offences. The accused is a first offender and has an immaculate driving record and has been a safe driver all these years.

25     It was raining heavily at the material time and the accused was travelling in the right-most lane when he failed to notice a large puddle of water ahead of him in the right-most lane. According to the Defence, he was not driving choc-a-block and was behind a taxi for quite a while. He saw the taxi in front of him and he thought it would be safer if he overtook the taxi. As he travelled over the puddle of water, he realised that he had lost control of the motor car which did not appear to respond to his steering or his repeated braking. His motor car then skidded and veered and ended up crashing through the road divider and onto the other side of the road, and then colliding into another oncoming vehicle.

26     It was further submitted that this was due to “hydroplaning” or “aquaplaning” (an occurrence which occurs when a layer of water builds between the wheels of a vehicle and the road surface causing the vehicle to lose their grip on the road surface and instead travel on the film of water, leading to a loss of traction that prevents the vehicle from responding to control inputs). The accused was immensely regretful and remorseful that he was involved in this accident and had caused injuries to the victims.

27     As a result of the collision, the accused also sustained serious injuries and he was taken to hospital where he underwent two major surgeries to treat internal injuries and haemorrhaging (small intestines). He was hospitalised and was discharged after about two weeks.

28     The Defence agreed with the Prosecution’s sentencing position and the mandatory disqualification period should be sufficient. It was the Defence’s position that the circumstances speak for itself and that there was no deliberate bad driving. It was highlighted that the accident took place in 2020. For various reasons, there were delays not caused by the accused. Had this case been dealt with earlier, the case of Sue Chang would not have been an issue.

Prosecution’s Reply

29     In response to the mitigation, it was submitted that the fact remained that the accused was travelling at a high speed and failed to have a proper control of the vehicle. At that point of time, it was raining and driving at such a high speed is dangerous. As regards the delay, it was highlighted that the case was filed in June 2022. The Attorney-General’s Chambers had directed the Investigation Officer to apply for the speed analysis report in October 2022 in view of representations sent by Counsel in September 2022.

Sentencing considerations

My decision on sentence

30     The accused had pleaded guilty to a charge under s 65(1)(a) punishable under s 65(3)(a) of the RTA. Another charge under s 65(1)(a) punishable under s 65(4)(a) of the Road Traffic Act was taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing.

Application of Sue Chang framework

31     In sentencing, I was bound by the 5-steps sentencing framework in Sue Chang which was prescribed by the Justice Vincent Hoong in his 5 July 2022 judgment for an offence under punishable under 65(3)(a) of the RTA. The first step is to identify the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of culpability of the offender.

Harm

32     The harm caused by the offence may be categorised into three levels of increasing severity: low, moderate and serious. Likewise, the offender’s culpability may be categorised into three levels: low, moderate and high.

33     In the present case, I considered that there was a total of four victims and two of the victims referred to in the proceeded charge suffered grievous hurt. The first victim suffered a comminuted fracture of the left calcaneum ie heel bone, with intraarticular involvement, as well as significant surrounding soft tissue swelling. He was hospitalised for a total of 12 days and was given 139 days of medical leave. He underwent left calcaneus corrective osteotomy and surgical fixation. The second victim sustained a right tibia ie shin bone fracture. She was hospitalised for 7 days and was given 20 days of medical leave. She had undergone a closed reduction and nailing of the right tibia on 8/3/2020 which was only removed 6 months later on 24 September 2020.

34     In addition, there were two other victims in respect of the charge that was taken into consideration. The third victim suffered facial laceration, a lung contusion and internal oblique muscle haematoma and right lower lateral incisor fracture. She was hospitalised for 3 days and was given 14 days of medical leave. The fourth victim sustained left neck abrasion, right knee and hip abrasion and was hospitalised from 2 days before being discharged with 16 days of medical leave.

Property damage

35     In addition, there are two other factors which may contribute to the severity of the harm caused, namely: (i) property damage; and (ii) potential harm. These factors are to be considered in tandem with the above descriptions of each level of harm. In the present case, in terms of the property damage caused, I took into account that the first victim’s car right side mirror was twisted, the front windscreen cracked and the front portion was cracked, crumpled, scratched, dented and twisted. From the vehicle damage report, I observed that the airbag was deployed after the collision. A portion of the guard railing was also uprooted.

Potential harm

36     The potential harm was significant as the accident had occurred along a stretch of road where the traffic volume was moderate and the speed limit was 70 km/h. It was only fortuitous that he had not collided into other vehicles travelling in the opposite direction when he lost control of his vehicle and hit the first victim’s car.

37     In my view, based on the above, the level of harm fell within the moderate range as two of the victims suffered fractures which necessitate some surgical procedures with a period of hospitalisation and significant periods of medical leave, property damage was occasioned as well as the degree of potential harm.

Culpability

38     In terms of culpability, I was mindful that it was raining at the material time, the road surface was wet and the traffic volume was moderate. Under such poor road conditions, the accused should have exercised extra care and consideration for his own personal safety as well as that of other road users. He ought to have driven at a speed lower than he normally would and kept a greater distance between his vehicles and other vehicles. As an experienced driver who would have been used to Singapore’s inclement weather conditions, the accused’s ought to have been alive to the risk of hydroplaning where his vehicle loses traction when he went through the puddle of water. Yet, from the HSA speed analysis report, the accused had driven high speeds above the prescribed speed limit of 70 km/h for at least 20 seconds before the collision with the victim’s car. Hence, it was clear that the accused had little regard or was oblivious to these road safety considerations as he travelled along Lornie Road.

39     It was the Defence’s position that the was not driving choc-a-block and was behind a taxi for quite a while. According to the Defence it was whipping quite a bit of water onto his windscreen. He saw the taxi in front of him and he thought it would be safer if he overtook the taxi. In my view, this assertion had little merit and was further unsupported by the objective evidence before me. From the HSA speed analysis report at Figure 1 from markings A to F as well as the footage from the accused’s in-vehicle camera, I observed that the accused had been travelling in lane 1 for some distance with no other vehicles ahead of him in lane 1 and had in fact driven past two different blue coloured taxis travelling in lane 2.

40     According to HSA’s speed analysis of the accused’s motorcar, he was travelling at an estimated average speed of 87km/h to 98 km/h in the 17 seconds prior to him losing control of his motorcar. In the last 3 seconds, the estimated average travelling speed was 88km/h to 102 km/h when the speed limit of the road was 70 km/h.

41     As for his manner of driving, I note that from the in-vehicle footage at 16:23:39 and the HSA speed analysis report, the accused was travelling on Lane 1 along Lornie Highway then Lornie Road towards Braddell Road/Thomson Road. At 16:23:57/58, he moved leftwards towards Lane 2 and subsequently steered to the right. At 16:23:59/162401, the car steered to the left and subsequently steered to the right again. At 16:24:01, the bonnet-of the car appeared to have shifted slightly (upwards and downwards), suggesting that the car had collided/mounted the central median. Subsequently, the car appeared to enter the opposite carriageway before it collided with the first victim’s vehicle.

42     Based on the above, as the accused was speeding and had made sudden movements from left to right then left to right again when the traffic conditions was poor, I was of the view that his level of culpability fell within the moderate range.

43     The second step is to identify the applicable indicative sentencing range in the sentencing matrix.

44     As I found that both the level of harm as well as culpability fell within the moderate range, the appropriate sentencing range is between 4 to 8 months’ imprisonment.

45     The third step is to identify the appropriate starting point within the indicative sentencing range. This is to be informed by the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of the offender’s culpability. In my view the appropriate starting point would be 4 months’ imprisonment.

46     The fourth step is to make adjustments to the starting point where necessary to take into account the offender-specific aggravating and mitigating factors. The fifth step which was to take into account the totality principle was not applicable as the Prosecution had proceeded on only one charge.

47     In the present case, I was mindful that the accused had pleaded guilty to the offence and is a first offender. Another charge under s 65(4)(a) of the RTA was taken into consideration for the purpose of sentence. Accordingly, I adjusted the appropriate sentence downwards as the Sue Chang framework is applicable to an offender who claims trial.

48     In the present case, I was of the view that the custodial threshold had clearly been crossed based on the facts of the present case and that a sentence of five weeks’ imprisonment and the mandatory minimum disqualification of five years with effect from release was just and appropriate as it combines the sentencing objectives of punishment, protection of the public and deterrence. With respect, the imposition of a fine of $4,000 to $5,000 sought by the Prosecution and the Defence was clearly wholly inadequate based on the moderate levels of harm as well as culpability in the present case.
